
  ---
  Current Supabase Integration Analysis

  What Supabase Does for SKUEL

  | Feature            | Status                 | Description                            |
  |--------------------|------------------------|----------------------------------------|
  | Password hashing   | ✅ Used                 | Supabase stores/verifies passwords     |
  | Email verification | ✅ Used                 | Sends confirmation emails              |
  | Password reset     | ✅ Used                 | Sends reset link emails                |
  | JWT tokens         | ⚠ Returned but unused | Sessions use Starlette cookies instead |
  | Database           | ❌ Not used             | Neo4j is the sole database             |
  | Storage            | ❌ Not used             | No file storage                        |
  | OAuth/Social       | ❌ Not used             | Only email/password                    |

  What SKUEL Already Has (Supabase-Independent)

  1. Bcrypt password hashing - /core/auth/password.py (fully functional)
  2. Session management - /core/auth/session.py (cookie-based, secure)
  3. User model - stores password_hash field (currently empty for Supabase users)
  4. User backend - full Neo4j CRUD for users

  Key insight: SKUEL is ~80% of the way to independent auth. The only missing pieces are:
  - Email sending (for verification/password reset)
  - Storing password hashes in Neo4j instead of Supabase

  ---
  Options for SKUEL-Owned Authentication

  Option 1: Native SKUEL Auth (Minimal Dependencies)

  Philosophy: Build directly on SKUEL's existing infrastructure

  What to add:
  - Email service (use resend, postmark, or SMTP)
  - Email verification tokens (stored in Neo4j)
  - Password reset tokens (stored in Neo4j)
  - Rate limiting for login attempts

  Existing infrastructure to leverage:
  # Already exists in SKUEL
  from core.auth.password import hash_password, verify_password  # bcrypt
  from core.auth.session import set_current_user, get_current_user  # cookies

  Pros:
  - 100% owned, zero external auth dependencies
  - Simple, fits SKUEL's "analog-to-digital" philosophy
  - Uses existing bcrypt and session infrastructure
  - Full control over UX and security

  Cons:
  - Must implement email verification flow
  - Must handle password reset emails
  - No social login (unless added later)

  ---
  Option 2: Add py_webauthn for Passkeys

  Philosophy: Modern, passwordless authentication

  Components:
  - https://github.com/duo-labs/py_webauthn - Pythonic WebAuthn library by Duo Labs
  - Keep password auth as fallback
  - Store passkey credentials in Neo4j

  Flow:
  Registration: User creates passkey → Store credential in Neo4j
  Login: User presents passkey → Verify with py_webauthn → Create session

  Pros:
  - Most secure (phishing-resistant)
  - Modern UX (Touch ID, Face ID, Windows Hello)
  - No passwords to store/hash
  - Standards-compliant (FIDO2/WebAuthn)

  Cons:
  - Requires device with biometrics
  - Need password fallback for recovery
  - More complex frontend integration

  ---
  Option 3: Self-Hosted Identity Server

  Options:

  | Server                       | Language | Notes                                  |
  |------------------------------|----------|----------------------------------------|
  | https://www.keycloak.org/    | Java     | Full-featured, enterprise-ready, heavy |
  | https://goauthentik.io/      | Python   | Modern UI, lighter than Keycloak       |
  | https://github.com/ory/hydra | Go       | Headless, OAuth2/OIDC certified        |
  | https://www.authelia.com/    | Go       | Simple SSO, works with Docker          |

  Pros:
  - Full OAuth2/OIDC compliance
  - Social login support out of the box
  - Enterprise features (LDAP, SAML)

  Cons:
  - Separate service to run/maintain
  - More infrastructure complexity
  - Overkill for single-application auth

  ---
  Recommendation: Option 1 (Native SKUEL Auth)

  Based on SKUEL's philosophy of "analog-to-digital" development and wanting code that "flows," I recommend Native SKUEL Auth:

  Migration Path

  Phase 1: Add email service
  ├── Add email dependency (resend, postmark, or SMTP)
  ├── Create EmailService protocol and implementation
  └── Test email sending

  Phase 2: Implement verification flow
  ├── Add verification_token to User model
  ├── Create /verify-email endpoint
  ├── Send verification email on registration
  └── Store password_hash in Neo4j (not Supabase)

  Phase 3: Implement password reset
  ├── Add reset_token to User model
  ├── Create /forgot-password and /reset-password endpoints
  └── Send reset email

  Phase 4: Remove Supabase
  ├── Migrate existing users (prompt password reset)
  ├── Remove SupabaseAuthService
  ├── Remove supabase_id from User model
  └── Remove supabase dependency from pyproject.toml

  Key Files to Modify

  | File                                       | Change                                |
  |--------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------|
  | core/auth/supabase_auth.py                 | Replace with core/auth/native_auth.py |
  | adapters/inbound/auth_routes.py            | Use native auth service               |
  | core/models/user/user.py                   | Use password_hash (already exists)    |
  | adapters/persistence/neo4j/user_backend.py | Already supports password storage     |

